column168: XPO Logistics terminal LHO experienced a release from a 5-gallon poly pail due to a puncture caused by improper dunnage. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-gallons of product released to 3' x 4' area of the trailer floor & a 3' x 3' area of the asphalt lot below due to a puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged pail & cleanup debris were then placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On April 3, 2023, at 1015 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Alachua, Florida regarding the release of approximately 1 gallon of Eco-San (Hypochlorite solutions, UN1791 8, III) and approximately 8 gallons of Ultra-San (Hypochlorite solutions, UN1791 8, III).  The releases were reportedly due to leaks in the product containers.  The release was contained to the trailer floor.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The released products, spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (3) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste drums were then transported off site for proper disposal.

On April 4, 2023, at 1730 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Falkville, Alabama regarding the release of approximately 1 quart of Neutrachill (Sodium hydroxide solution, UN1824 8, II).  The release was contained to a 1’ x 6’ area of the trailer floor.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE. XPO Logistics terminal LDA experienced a UN2920 1,1,3,3-Tetramethylguanidine release from a 55-gallon metal drum due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractor to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product was released to a 3’ x 3’ area of the trailer floor and a 3’ x 3’ area to the asphalt underneath the trailer. The drum was punctured by improper loading. Absorbents and neutralizers were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. All material was collected and containerized into a 55 and 95-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics Terminal XPB experienced a release of UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid Solution from a box containing 34-ounce glass bottles. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately 1-tablespoon of the product was released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the cardboard packaging. The bottle was cracked by falling on the trailer floor due to improper loading. All material was collected and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics Terminal UBY experienced a UN1760 "Clothesline Fresh Xtreme Laundry Sour" release from (2) 5-gallon poly pails due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed that 2 pails of Clothesline Fresh Xtreme Laundry Sour released approximately 2-ounces of to a 2’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor. The pails were crushed by the pallet falling over during transit due to improper securement. Absorbents and neutralizers were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. All released product was collected and containerized into a 15-gallon & 55-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: RESPONDED TO A PACKAGE THAT WAS COLD TO THE TOUCH WITH FROST FORMING ON THE OUTER BOX. UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS DISCOVERED SEVERAL POUNDS OF DRY ICE PELLETS COOLING FOOD. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER BOX INDICTING DRY ICE WAS BEING SHIPPED. OUTER BOX IS PREPRINTED AS PERISHABLE, HANDLE WITH CARE, AND REFRIGERATE UPON ARRIVAL. THERE IS ALSO A LIST OF FOOD ITEMS ON A PRINTED STICKER AFFIXED TO THE BOX.

XPO Logistics Terminal XAY experienced a UN2428 "RE/GEN CC-45" release from a 30-gallon poly drum due to improper packaging. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to an 8’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor and a 2’ x 3’ area to the asphalt yard underneath the trailer. Crew found that the threading on the drum cap was damaged. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. All impacted pallet wood was placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The impacted absorbents and PPE were placed into a separate 55-gallon poly drum. All lids and bung caps were vented as precaution. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Around 5pm central time I received a call from Toby Owens who works for Bozeman. Toby told me he was fueling up at the Loves at 335 LA-594, Monroe, LA, 71203 and was doing a walk around of set and noticed a pool of paint (UN1263, Paint, 3, PGIII) on ground and that it was still leaking from his rear pup (287281F). Toby notified central dispatch and they told him to contact Billy or myself. I contacted Hazmat One at 524pm and told them to make all the necessary phone calls and to take all waste with them. Toby mentioned it started to rain and Loves Truck Stop helped contain the spill from spreading more. Hazmat One arrived at Loves at 835pm to start cleaning spill. Hazmat One is renting a boom to unload trailer to clean up. They believe the leak is coming from a drum in nose of trailer. They projected a time of 600am to have spill cleaned up. Release was caused by a nail in the pallet the drums were loaded on. The nail during transit had punctured a hole in the bottom on one drum. Majority of material had leaked into the trailer
column169: Shipper will be notified of incident and that it could have been prevented with a better inspection of pallet.

column168: Haz-Mat Response Inc. (HMRI) was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed  that the released material impacted a  6ft- by-25ft area of the trailer floor and  trailer bumper and estimated that five (5) gallons of material was released from one 5-gallon metal drum due to improper securement for transport that caused the cargo to shift. HMRI personnel used absorbent pads to collect the material. HMRI personnel used a forklift to offload  the  trailer  to  clean  the  trailer  floor  and  restack  the  undamaged  cargo  to  forward  on  to  the consignee. The spent absorbent pads and debris was placed into one (1) 30-gallon poly drum and was transported offsite by HMRI personnel to process for disposal.
